at the table, the software, it reads this...

1192
01:33:06,989 --> 01:33:08,456
Biometric profile.

1193
01:33:08,557 --> 01:33:10,320
...biometric profile of your face,

1194
01:33:10,426 --> 01:33:13,452
cross-references it
with a database of counters.

1195
01:33:16,999 --> 01:33:21,800
Software'll probably put you and me
out of business, but it still can't do this.

1196
01:33:24,975 --> 01:33:26,272
All right.

1197
01:33:31,847 --> 01:33:34,714
You understand all this. You go to MIT.

1198
01:33:35,084 --> 01:33:36,483
Smart boy.

1199
01:33:37,953 --> 01:33:39,887
My name is Cole Williams.

1200
01:33:40,490 --> 01:33:43,755
And if I ever see you in this town again,

1201
01:33:44,528 --> 01:33:47,928
I will break your cheek bone
with a small hammer,

1202
01:33:49,165 --> 01:33:51,156
and then I will kill you.

1203
01:33:55,838 --> 01:33:59,400
Please. Please just take the money.

1204
01:34:00,644 --> 01:34:02,168
You can take it.

1205
01:34:04,881 --> 01:34:06,212
Tell me,

1206
01:34:06,783 --> 01:34:11,515
how's good old Professor Rosa doing, huh?

1207
01:34:13,189 --> 01:34:17,786
Oh, yeah. Me and Micky, we go way back.

1208
01:34:18,895 --> 01:34:21,887
I spent years, chased him all over this town.

1209
01:34:22,332 --> 01:34:27,292
Giving him beat downs left and right,
only to find him at the tables a week later.

1210
01:34:27,404 --> 01:34:29,372
He was very persistent.

1211
01:34:30,272 --> 01:34:33,572
And then, one September night,

1212
01:34:34,077 --> 01:34:36,978
when I was in Barstow
at my father's funeral,

1213
01:34:37,848 --> 01:34:41,284
my casino was taken for seven figures.

1214
01:34:41,385 --> 01:34:42,716
Can you imagine that?

1215
01:34:42,819 --> 01:34:46,050
The most ever taken by a single counter
in one night.

1216
01:34:46,156 --> 01:34:50,752
'Course I was, naturally,
unceremoniously fired.

1217
01:34:53,463 --> 01:34:55,226
Funny thing, though.

1218
01:34:55,632 --> 01:34:58,157
I never saw Micky Rosa after that.

1219
01:34:59,336 --> 01:35:00,462
Never.

1220
01:36:27,191 --> 01:36:29,318
<i>Cauchy was the first
to make a rigorous study</i>

1221
01:36:29,427 --> 01:36:33,455
of the conditions for convergence
of an infinite series.

1222
01:36:33,565 --> 01:36:35,863
And was concerned with developing

1223
01:36:35,967 --> 01:36:40,836
the basic theorems of the calculus
as rigorously as possible.

1224
01:36:42,240 --> 01:36:43,673
Any questions?

1225
01:36:44,075 --> 01:36:46,202
No? All right, moving on.

1226
01:36:47,246 --> 01:36:51,239
Isn't it true Cauchy stole from his students?

1227
01:36:56,154 --> 01:37:00,021
Yes, I heard that.
What's your theory on that?

1228
01:37:01,058 --> 01:37:05,587
They say he used his students
for their brilliance,

1229
01:37:06,732 --> 01:37:10,964
then discredited them
and stole their equations,

1230
01:37:13,038 --> 01:37:14,903
stole their hard work.

1231
01:37:17,609 --> 01:37:20,304
Well, that wouldn't be the first time
a teacher was accused of that.

1232
01:37:20,411 --> 01:37:25,111
I think what he's referring to
is Vladimir Stupnitsky, yes?

1233
01:37:25,217 --> 01:37:28,152
He was a student of Cauchy's
who accused Cauchy

1234
01:37:28,253 --> 01:37:31,586
of stealing his four-volume text
on this analysis

1235
01:37:31,690 --> 01:37:34,158
and publishing it under a pseudonym.

1236
01:37:35,994 --> 01:37:37,655
Of course, nobody knows
what really went down there.

1237
01:37:37,764 --> 01:37:41,756
They never did prove it, and without
the proof, it's a little like it never happened.

1238
01:37:41,867 --> 01:37:43,892
And, you know, it's a real shame,

1239
01:37:44,002 --> 01:37:48,200
because if Stupnitsky had just realized
that he shouldn't have crossed Cauchy,

1240
01:37:48,307 --> 01:37:50,036
this was the dispute,

1241
01:37:51,076 --> 01:37:57,073
if he'd been able to get beyond some
of the personal mistakes that were made,

1242
01:37:57,617 --> 01:38:00,847
I have no doubt that Cauchy
would have worked with him again,

1243
01:38:00,953 --> 01:38:03,979
and they could have
done great things together.

1244
01:38:04,389 --> 01:38:08,450
But, as history shows us,
some students never learn.

1245
01:38:10,162 --> 01:38:11,824
You should get that eye looked at.

1246
01:38:49,035 --> 01:38:50,434
You okay?

1247
01:38:53,406 --> 01:38:55,033
Everything's gone.

1248
01:38:56,843 --> 01:38:59,437
- What?
- Micky's taken everything.

1249
01:38:59,545 --> 01:39:03,777
He's taken the money,
taken away Harvard Med, even MIT.

1250
01:39:05,652 --> 01:39:07,745
- What are you talking about?
- Micky, he's taken everything.

1251
01:39:07,854 --> 01:39:10,254
I gotta find a way to get it back.

1252
01:39:11,557 --> 01:39:13,047
Are you insane?

1253
01:39:13,660 --> 01:39:17,221
You just got the shit kicked out of you
and you won't let this go!

1254
01:39:17,330 --> 01:39:21,267
Look, what am I supposed to do, Jill?
I've just lost everything!

1255
01:39:22,036 --> 01:39:23,526
Look, please...

1256
01:39:25,338 --> 01:39:27,602
I don't want to lose you, too.

1257
01:39:30,610 --> 01:39:34,205
Ben, you were dragged away in Vegas.

1258
01:39:34,881 --> 01:39:39,216
I haven't heard from you.
I had no idea where you were.

1259
01:39:39,920 --> 01:39:41,148
I know.

1260
01:39:42,122 --> 01:39:43,282
I know.

1261
01:39:50,630 --> 01:39:53,428
You know, I'm so sorry that I hurt you.

1262
01:39:55,235 --> 01:39:56,600
I'm sorry.

1263
01:39:59,473 --> 01:40:03,967
In Vegas, I don't know what happened.
That wasn't me.

1264
01:40:05,179 --> 01:40:06,805
Look, you know me.

1265
01:40:07,513 --> 01:40:09,378
You know what I'm like.

1266
01:40:11,185 --> 01:40:12,675
You know me.

1267
01:40:19,126 --> 01:40:20,991
I need you to trust me.

1268
01:40:22,329 --> 01:40:25,696
<i>And the winner of this year's 2.09</i>

1269
01:40:25,799 --> 01:40:32,068
<i>for excellence in the field of robotics
goes to the team of Conolly and Kazazi!</i>

1270
01:41:09,443 --> 01:41:12,412
That's it. That's the story.

1271
01:41:14,915 --> 01:41:17,145
Jill Taylor. Really?

1272
01:41:17,951 --> 01:41:21,444
- Yeah. Yeah, really.
- Wow.

1273
01:41:21,556 --> 01:41:25,754
<i>Yeah, it doesn't feel like " wow," Miles.
I really screwed up.</i>

1274
01:41:25,860 --> 01:41:30,592
Yeah, you did.
But you had a life experience.

1275
01:41:35,035 --> 01:41:37,027
I can't believe how I treated you, Miles.

1276
01:41:37,138 --> 01:41:41,040
You know, you're my best friend,
and I really let you down.

1277
01:41:41,910 --> 01:41:45,004
I really let you down. I'm sorry.

1278
01:41:46,815 --> 01:41:51,343
And I'm happy for you, you know?
Winning the 2.09? That's great.

1279
01:41:52,720 --> 01:41:55,188
- Jill Taylor. Really?
- Yeah.

1280
01:41:57,725 --> 01:41:59,818
So let me get this straight.

1281
01:42:00,495 --> 01:42:03,658
Money, girls,

1282
01:42:04,833 --> 01:42:09,236
high-roller suites, clubs, Vegas.

1283
01:42:10,439 --> 01:42:15,466
Yeah, I think I probably would have
blown off the 2.09 Competition, too.

1284
01:42:19,013 --> 01:42:20,378
So we cool?

1285
01:42:22,016 --> 01:42:23,608
Yeah, we're cool.

1286
01:42:24,118 --> 01:42:26,815
But you better believe that
you're gonna make this up to me, big time.

1287
01:42:26,922 --> 01:42:28,184
All right.

1288
01:42:29,491 --> 01:42:31,618
So, what are you gonna do now?

1289
01:43:22,411 --> 01:43:24,242
What do you want, Ben?
This is an alumni dinner.

1290
01:43:24,346 --> 01:43:26,712
You need a diploma
to come to one of these.

1291
01:43:26,815 --> 01:43:29,215
Wait. Stupnitsky wants back in.

1292
01:43:35,425 --> 01:43:36,392
What?

1293
01:43:36,493 --> 01:43:40,622
Look, I've had some time
to think about what you said.

1294
01:43:42,498 --> 01:43:43,988
I want back in.

1295
01:43:44,967 --> 01:43:48,835
- Why now?
- Because I have nothing else.

1296
01:43:50,706 --> 01:43:53,904
All right, look, Ben. I'm not gonna lie to you.
You're good, you're very, very good.

1297
01:43:54,010 --> 01:43:58,173
But you did exactly what I told you not to.
You got emotional and then you got stupid.

1298
01:43:58,280 --> 01:44:01,977
Now you tell me why in the world
I'd ever get back in business with you.

1299
01:44:02,084 --> 01:44:06,544
Look, I know I should never have
disrespected you, all right? I know that.

1300
01:44:07,523 --> 01:44:09,492
With this facial recognition software,

1301
01:44:09,592 --> 01:44:12,789
our window of opportunity
is closing in on us.

1302
01:44:13,330 --> 01:44:16,993
Now, I need this, Micky.
I really, really need this.

1303
01:44:17,100 --> 01:44:22,230
Well, the take would have to be really, really
good to get me even vaguely interested.

1304
01:44:23,739 --> 01:44:29,042
Well, you know, that's why I was thinking
maybe you should be the other big player.

1305
01:44:30,447 --> 01:44:33,780
You know, two big players playing big?

1306
01:44:34,951 --> 01:44:38,284
Hey, slow down,
I haven't played in a long time, Ben.

1307
01:44:42,726 --> 01:44:44,318
But Fisher's out.

1308
01:44:45,195 --> 01:44:49,564
No one else on the team
can be the big player, can they?

1309
01:44:52,802 --> 01:44:56,203
And if we do well, if we do really well,

1310
01:44:56,973 --> 01:45:00,137
then you get your grades back,
get to Harvard Med,

1311
01:45:01,144 --> 01:45:03,669
and I might even get that sabbatical.

1312
01:45:04,681 --> 01:45:09,141
Well, amazing things can be done
from the inside, right?

1313
01:45:11,087 --> 01:45:13,783
Just went back to the head of the class.

1314
01:45:15,058 --> 01:45:16,924
I gotta go be social.

1315
01:45:22,298 --> 01:45:25,597
All right, now listen.
It's different out there this time.

1316
01:45:25,702 --> 01:45:28,569
The stakes are high
and it's more dangerous.

1317
01:45:29,105 --> 01:45:32,165
But the return is gonna be the biggest.

1318
01:45:33,477 --> 01:45:36,913
Now they know our faces,
so we're gonna wear disguises.

1319
01:45:37,148 --> 01:45:39,116
And we can't mess around.

1320
01:45:39,483 --> 01:45:40,950
I'm glad you're back with us, Micky.

1321
01:45:41,052 --> 01:45:42,951
Well, I couldn't let you guys
come back to this town

1322
01:45:43,053 --> 01:45:46,545
and not prove to Ben
that I can do more than just teach.

1323
01:45:47,390 --> 01:45:51,293
But as we've all said, this game
is about the past and the future,

1324
01:45:51,395 --> 01:45:54,455
and tonight we forget about the past.

1325
01:45:54,698 --> 01:45:56,563
We just focus on the future.

1326
01:45:56,667 --> 01:46:00,000
Right. This is our last time.

1327
01:46:00,404 --> 01:46:03,430
Now, we all know the drill if things get ugly.
We meet at the Fox Strip Club.

1328
01:46:03,541 --> 01:46:05,872
Nobody leaves this town alone.

1329
01:46:09,346 --> 01:46:11,246
Let's go make a killing.

1330
01:46:11,782 --> 01:46:13,147
All right.

1331
01:46:35,272 --> 01:46:37,740
Let's see what we can do with this.

1332
01:46:46,851 --> 01:46:50,912
Seems like I'm having one of those days,
you know what I mean, Jim?

1333
01:46:52,590 --> 01:46:54,717
I'm bringing all the luck today.
I'm just bringing it all.

1334
01:46:54,825 --> 01:46:59,286
Anyone who's in any kind of contact
with me is getting so much luck today.

1335
01:47:10,941 --> 01:47:13,102
Winner, winner, chicken dinner! There it is.

1336
01:47:13,210 --> 01:47:16,647
Thank you. God, I love this town.
I love this game.

1337
01:47:17,449 --> 01:47:20,748
And, Jim, I might even love you.

1338
01:47:30,561 --> 01:47:32,757
Hey, you mind if I sit down?

1339
01:47:46,778 --> 01:47:47,836
What's your name?

1340
01:47:47,946 --> 01:47:51,074
Shane? I'm about to change your luck.
It's gonna become mine.

1341
01:47:51,183 --> 01:47:53,413
There you go, give me it all.

1342
01:48:03,461 --> 01:48:04,655
There you go.

1343
01:48:07,433 --> 01:48:09,196
Thank you. Thank you.

1344
01:48:13,939 --> 01:48:16,169
Such a shame, Shane!

1345
01:48:17,142 --> 01:48:19,201
Okay, I'm supposed to double, right?

1346
01:48:19,311 --> 01:48:23,646
- Is this your first time, darling?
- I've been winning and losing for hours.

1347
01:48:23,749 --> 01:48:25,842
Well, that's all right.
I've been winning and losing for years.

1348
01:48:39,164 --> 01:48:40,689
What the hell kind of streak
are you on, boy?

1349
01:48:40,800 --> 01:48:43,462
This never happens, this never happens.

1350
01:48:56,514 --> 01:48:58,312
I'm just gonna have to split those tens.

1351
01:48:58,417 --> 01:48:59,975
- Splitting tens.
- Splitting tens!

1352
01:49:00,086 --> 01:49:01,948
- Split tens!
- Again!

1353
01:49:24,877 --> 01:49:27,846
- Thank you, ma'am.
- Give me the chips, Blanca.

1354
01:49:29,081 --> 01:49:30,947
Give me the chips!
Come on, give me the chips, Blanca.

1355
01:49:31,051 --> 01:49:33,952
Come on, just give me the chips!

1356
01:49:34,054 --> 01:49:38,183
- My bus has to leave right away.
- I gotta walk my dog.

1357
01:49:38,291 --> 01:49:40,851
- I'm sorry we're making such a mess.
- Go, go, go, go, go.

1358
01:49:40,960 --> 01:49:44,020
Nice to see you. Have a good night, darling.

1359
01:49:49,569 --> 01:49:50,866
This way!

1360
01:50:02,081 --> 01:50:03,173
Go.

1361
01:50:17,530 --> 01:50:18,895
This way!

1362
01:50:24,805 --> 01:50:26,796
Come on, Jill. Come on!

1363
01:50:36,717 --> 01:50:39,311
Go that way. Throw me the chips.
Come on, we gotta separate.

1364
01:50:39,419 --> 01:50:42,286
Give me the chips, I'll meet you at Fox's.

1365
01:50:48,362 --> 01:50:49,954
Go, go, go, go!

1366
01:51:00,907 --> 01:51:02,568
Come on, come on.

1367
01:51:05,679 --> 01:51:07,237
Move, move, move!

1368
01:51:11,418 --> 01:51:12,680
Come on.

1369
01:51:13,821 --> 01:51:15,413
Go, go, this way.

1370
01:51:27,401 --> 01:51:29,232
All right, let's go.

1371
01:51:37,311 --> 01:51:39,802
Go, go, go, go! Airport!

1372
01:51:58,366 --> 01:51:59,993
<i>I never saw Micky Rosa after that.</i>

1373
01:52:05,072 --> 01:52:06,334
Oh, God.

1374
01:52:07,442 --> 01:52:09,706
But I think I wanna see him now.

1375
01:52:10,778 --> 01:52:13,246
And I want you to make that happen.

1376
01:52:17,518 --> 01:52:19,952
I don't work for Micky anymore.

1377
01:52:22,957 --> 01:52:24,390
Come on, kid.

1378
01:52:26,227 --> 01:52:29,993
Your picture's all over the database.
Your Vegas gig is done.

1379
01:52:31,032 --> 01:52:32,966
But I will give you one night.

1380
01:52:33,067 --> 01:52:36,127
And I can guarantee
that you won't be bothered.

1381
01:52:37,038 --> 01:52:40,805
You'll make a killing, and you'll keep it all.

1382
01:52:43,878 --> 01:52:45,072
Listen.

1383
01:52:46,647 --> 01:52:48,114
My name's Cole.

1384
01:52:49,684 --> 01:52:51,208
Cole Williams.

1385
01:52:53,120 --> 01:52:55,521
You just bring me Micky Rosa, kid.

1386
01:52:55,824 --> 01:52:57,849
I'll take care of the rest.

1387
01:53:00,395 --> 01:53:03,330
Son of a bitch.

1388
01:53:45,975 --> 01:53:47,737
Who the hell are you?

1389
01:54:10,599 --> 01:54:13,762
Ben. Good job.

1390
01:54:14,836 --> 01:54:19,900
You'll be glad to know I'm gonna have a talk
with your professor, and that MIT thing?

1391
01:54:20,109 --> 01:54:22,202
It's gonna work out for you.

1392
01:54:23,780 --> 01:54:25,338
So that's it?

1393
01:54:26,783 --> 01:54:29,546
- That's it.
- All right.

1394
01:54:30,519 --> 01:54:32,214
Oh, Dr. Campbell?

1395
01:54:33,555 --> 01:54:36,525
They don't have pensions
in my line of work.

1396
01:54:36,859 --> 01:54:38,759
And the software does
what it's supposed to do.

1397
01:54:38,861 --> 01:54:42,763
And I been chasing Micky Rosa around here
for too damn long.

1398
01:54:44,000 --> 01:54:46,264
I'm looking at some retirement.

1399
01:54:48,171 --> 01:54:49,638
Leave the bag.

1400
01:54:51,707 --> 01:54:54,006
No. No, no, no, no.

1401
01:54:54,110 --> 01:54:58,604
I need this money. You have no idea
what I went through to get this money.

1402
01:54:58,715 --> 01:55:03,709
I know, kid, but you're gonna figure out
how to get everything you want in this life,

1403
01:55:03,820 --> 01:55:05,549
'cause you're smart.

1404
01:55:07,123 --> 01:55:11,651
So, you're gonna leave the bag.

1405
01:55:16,699 --> 01:55:21,295
Ben, give him the bag. Give him the bag.
It doesn't matter. Give him the bag.

1406
01:55:30,147 --> 01:55:31,944
I knew you were smart.

1407
01:55:50,801 --> 01:55:53,530
<i>I had a 1590 on my SAT.</i>

1408
01:55:53,636 --> 01:55:55,695
<i>I got a 44 on my MCATs.</i>

1409
01:55:56,205 --> 01:55:59,333
<i>And I have a 4.0 GPA from MIT.</i>

1410
01:55:59,442 --> 01:56:01,911
<i>I thought I had my life mapped out.</i>

1411
01:56:03,814 --> 01:56:04,906
<i>But then I remembered</i>

1412
01:56:05,015 --> 01:56:08,473
<i>what my Nonlinear Equations professor
once told me,</i>

1413
01:56:09,019 --> 01:56:12,250
<i>"Always account for variable change."</i>

1414
01:56:14,058 --> 01:56:15,581
Hello, Micky.

1415
01:56:17,293 --> 01:56:19,125
Look, I got money in Boston.
A hundred grand.

1416
01:56:19,229 --> 01:56:21,254
I'll give it to you.
Just let me walk away. I'll walk away.

1417
01:56:21,365 --> 01:56:24,425
I don't want your money, Micky.
I don't need it.

1418
01:56:30,240 --> 01:56:33,038
But I know someone
who might be interested.

1419
01:56:33,410 --> 01:56:37,506
He's good with numbers, too.
He works for the IRS.

1420
01:56:46,323 --> 01:56:48,382
<i>I let down my good friends.</i>

1421
01:56:49,059 --> 01:56:53,997
<i>But as it turns out,
they weren't too bad at simple math either.</i>

1422
01:57:19,823 --> 01:57:22,383
<i>I scored the prettiest girl in school.</i>

1423
01:57:25,863 --> 01:57:28,492
<i>I got beaten down
by an old-school Vegas thug</i>

1424
01:57:28,600 --> 01:57:31,797
<i>who was having trouble
accepting his retirement.</i>

1425
01:57:33,104 --> 01:57:36,870
<i>But I worked out a deal with him
that got him a nice pension.</i>

